{"title": "Show HN: Combine WigglyPaint GIFs into Video", "link": "https://altbdoor.github.io/wiggly-compose-gif/", "summary": "<p>Been trying out WigglyPaint[1] lately to flesh out my creative side. I started drawing a series of images, and wanted to combine them into a video to post into social media.<p>The first iteration I did was manually mangling FFmpeg commands to loop GIFs over n seconds, before combining them into a video. After that I thought, I might as well make a web application to help make this easier.<p>Ironically, the videos I created in my Firefox Windows appears to be unplayable, which prompted me to go full circle, by importing a FFmpeg WASM to fix the file.<p>But it was definitely interesting to see how the JS code work to splice GIFs into image data, replaying it over a canvas, which then feeds to a WebCodec. GitHub link is in [2] if you are interested to see the source code. Cheers!<p>[1]: <a href=\"https://beyondloom.com/tools/wigglypaint.html#main\" rel=\"nofollow\">https://beyondloom.com/tools/wigglypaint.html#main</a><p>[2]: <a href=\"https://github.com/altbdoor/wiggly-compose-gif\" rel=\"nofollow\">https://github.com/altbdoor/wiggly-compose-gif</a></p>\n<hr />\n<p>Comments URL: <a href=\"https://news.ycombinator.com/item?id=48353070\">https://news.ycombinator.com/item?id=48353070</a></p>\n<p>Points: 1</p>\n<p># Comments: 0</p>", "published": "2026-06-01T05:49:06+00:00", "source": "Hacker News Best", "category": "techblog", "matched_entities": {}, "ontology": {"repo": "BlogRadar", "category": "techblog", "ontology_version": "0.1.0", "source_event_model": "blog_post", "event_model_id": "tech.blog_post", "evidence_policy_ids": ["source_metadata", "article_text"], "event_model_payload": {"headline": "Show HN: Combine WigglyPaint GIFs into Video", "source_name": "Hacker News Best", "source_url": "https://altbdoor.github.io/wiggly-compose-gif/", "published_at": "2026-06-01T05:49:06+00:00", "summary": "<p>Been trying out WigglyPaint[1] lately to flesh out my creative side. I started drawing a series of images, and wanted to combine them into a video to post into social media.<p>The first iteration I did was manually mangling FFmpeg commands to loop GIFs over n seconds, before combining them into a video. After that I thought, I might as well make a web application to help make this easier.<p>Ironically, the videos I created in my Firefox Windows appears to be unplayable, which prompted me to go full circle, by importing a FFmpeg WASM to fix the file.<p>But it was definitely interesting to see how the JS code work to splice GIFs into image data, replaying it over a canvas, which then feeds to a WebCodec. GitHub link is in [2] if you are interested to see the source code. Cheers!<p>[1]: <a href=\"https://beyondloom.com/tools/wigglypaint.html#main\" rel=\"nofollow\">https://beyondloom.com/tools/wigglypaint.html#main</a><p>[2]: <a href=\"https://github.com/altbdoor/wiggly-compose-gif\" rel=\"nofollow\">https://github.com/altbdoor/wiggly-compose-gif</a></p>\n<hr />\n<p>Comments URL: <a href=\"https://news.ycombinator.com/item?id=48353070\">https://news.ycombinator.com/item?id=48353070</a></p>\n<p>Points: 1</p>\n<p># Comments: 0</p>"}}, "logged_at": "2026-06-01T06:02:59.640514+00:00"}
